Class MoreMaps

    • com.bluegosling.collections.MoreMaps

  • public final class MoreMaps

    Utility methods for working with and creating instanceos of Map. These methods complement those in Guava's Maps class.

    • Method Detail

      • fromCollection

        public static <T> Map<T,T> fromCollection(Collection<T> coll)
        Returns a view of the given collection as an identity map. In the map, the value associated with each key is the key itself. Putting new entries in the map is supported, but only if the given key and value are equal. Otherwise, an IllegalArgumentException is thrown.

        If the given collection contains duplicates, they are ignored to preserve the property that keys in a map are distinct.

        Unlike most map implementations, the Map.size() operation (and operations of the same name for collection views returned by the map) may run in linear time instead of constant time (in order to count distinct keys, in case there are duplicates). If the given collection implements Set, then size can be determined in constant time. Similarly, queries on the map, like Map.containsKey(Object) or Map.get(Object), will take linear time unless the given collection implements Set (in which case they run in the same time as Set.contains(Object), usually sub-linear).

        Parameters:
        coll - a collection
        Returns:
        a view of the collection as an identity map

      • zip

        public static <K,V> Map<K,V> zip(Iterable<? extends K> keys,
                                 Iterable<? extends V> values)
        Combines the given iterables into a map, "zipping" the elements into key-value pairs. So a key is taken from the first iterable, and its associated value in the resulting map is the value taken from the second iterable. When either stream is exhausted, the combined stream is also exhausted. So if one stream has more items than the other, the extra items in the longer stream are ignored.

        The given sequence of keys must be distinct. If duplicates are encountered, an IllegalArgumentException is thrown.

        Parameters:
        keys - the sequence of keys
        values - the sequence of values
        Returns:
        a map comprised of the given keys and values
